Investigate a "No-show appointments" Dataset
¶

Introduction¶

Appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.¶

  • ‘ScheduledDay’ tells us on what day the patient set up their appointment.
  • ‘Neighborhood’ indicates the location of the hospital.
  • ‘Scholarship’ indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família(opens in a new tab).
Be careful about the encoding of the last column: it says ‘No’ if the patient showed up to their appointment, and ‘Yes’ if they did not show up.¶

This dataset was taken from MedicalAppointmentNoShows.¶

Questions¶

  • Q1: Does Gender Affect the Attendence?
  • Q2: Does Age Affect the Attendance?
  • Q3: Does Neighbourhood Affect the Attendance?
  • Q4: Does Scholarship Affect the Attendance?
  • Q5: Does SMS Affect the Attendance?
  • Q6: Does Handicap Affect the Attendance?
  • Q7: Does Age and Chronic Deseases (Diabetes, Hypertension) Affect the Attendence?
  • Q8: Does Nighbourhood and Age Affect the Attendance?
  • Q9: Does Neighbourhood and SMS Affect the Attendance?

Q2)_ Does Age Affect the Attendance?¶

In [120]:
# Create a boolean mask for rows where 'No_show' is 'No' (attended)
attend = df['No_show'] == 'No'
# Create a boolean mask for rows where 'No_show' is 'Yes' (absent)
absent = df['No_show'] == 'Yes'
# Create a new figure with the specified size
plt.figure(figsize=[15, 6])
# Plot a Kernel Density Estimate (KDE) plot for the 'Age' column of attendees
# The 'shade=True' parameter fills the area under the KDE curve
sns.kdeplot(df[attend]['Age'], shade=True, color='blue', label='Attend')
# Plot a KDE plot for the 'Age' column of absentees
sns.kdeplot(df[absent]['Age'], shade=True, color='red', label='Absent')
# Add a legend to the plot to differentiate between attendees and absentees
plt.legend()
# Set the title of the plot
plt.title('Compare Attendance Status According to Age')
# Set the label for the x-axis
plt.xlabel('Age')
# Set the label for the y-axis
plt.ylabel('Density')
# Display the plot
plt.show()

Answer : We can clearly see there is no relation between age, attendance, or absence; the two charts did not like each other.¶

#we see there is a code repeted so here is a fuction to avoid the repete for count plot
def plot_attendance_status(column, x_labels, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax = sns.countplot(x=column, hue='No_show', data=df)
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.set_xticklabels(x_labels)
    plt.show()

Q7)_ Does Age and Chronic Deseases (Diabetes, Hypertension) Affect the Attendence?¶

In [96]:
# Calculate mean age for attendees grouped by Diabetes and Hypertension
attend_means = df[attend].groupby(['Diabetes', 'Hypertension']).Age.mean().reset_index()

# Calculate mean age for absentees grouped by Diabetes and Hypertension
absent_means = df[absent].groupby(['Diabetes', 'Hypertension']).Age.mean().reset_index()
# Merge the two DataFrames on Diabetes and Hypertension
mean_age_comparison = pd.merge(attend_means, absent_means, on=['Diabetes', 'Hypertension'], suffixes=('_Attend', '_Absent'))
# Melt the DataFrame for easier plotting with seaborn
mean_age_comparison_melted = mean_age_comparison.melt(id_vars=['Diabetes', 'Hypertension'], 
                                                      value_vars=['Age_Attend', 'Age_Absent'], 
                                                      var_name='Status', 
                                                      value_name='Mean Age')
# Create a new figure with specified size
plt.figure(figsize=[16, 6])
# Create a bar plot using seaborn
sns.barplot(data=mean_age_comparison_melted, x='Diabetes', y='Mean Age', hue='Status', 
            palette=['blue', 'red'], ci=None, dodge=True)
# Set the plot title
plt.title('Comparison According to Age and Chronic Diseases')
# Set the x-axis label
plt.xlabel('Chronic Diseases (0 = No, 1 = Yes)')
# Set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Mean Age')
# Add a legend with title
plt.legend(title='Attendance Status')
# Display the plot
plt.show()

Answer : It Not effect the Chronic Deseases of the Attendance the same ratio for both¶

Q9)_ Does Neighbourhood and SMS Affect the Attendance?¶

In [98]:
# Calculate mean SMS received for attendees grouped by Neighbourhood
mean_sms_attend = df[df['No_show'] == 'No'].groupby('Neighbourhood')['SMS_received'].mean()
# Calculate mean SMS received for absentees grouped by Neighbourhood
mean_sms_absent = df[df['No_show'] == 'Yes'].groupby('Neighbourhood')['SMS_received'].mean()
# Combine the mean SMS data into a DataFrame and fill NaNs with 0
mean_sms_combined = pd.DataFrame({'Attend': mean_sms_attend, 'Absent': mean_sms_absent}).fillna(0).reset_index()
# Pivot the DataFrame for the heatmap
mean_sms_pivot = mean_sms_combined.pivot(index='Neighbourhood', columns='Attend', values='Absent')
# Create a new figure with specified size
plt.figure(figsize=[20, 10])
# Create a heatmap using seaborn
sns.heatmap(mean_sms_pivot, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f")
# Set the plot title
plt.title('Heatmap of Mean SMS Received by Neighbourhood and Attendance Status')
# Set the x-axis label
plt.xlabel('Attendance Status')
# Set the y-axis label
plt.ylabel('Neighbourhood')
# Display the plot
plt.show()

Conclusions

The goal of this investigation was to identify the variables that affect Brazilian patients' attendance at doctor's appointments. The dataset contains many attributes for every patient, including the day of the appointment, the hospital's area, and the patient's enrollment status in the Brazilian assistance program Bolsa Família. The 'No-show' column, of particular note, shows 'Yes' if the patient missed their appointment and 'No' if they did.¶

  • Gender and attendance: After investigating and exploring the data, we did not find a clear relationship between gender and attendance. Both males and females exhibited similar patterns of attendance and non-attendance.

  • Age and attendance: Contrary to our initial expectations, we did not observe a significant relationship between age and non-attendance. The data did not indicate a strong correlation between these variables.

  • Neighborhood and attendance: The analysis did not reveal a distinct relationship between the neighborhood of the patient and their likelihood of attending appointments. Attendance rates appeared to increase proportionally with the number of patients from each area, suggesting no specific neighborhood effect.

  • Grant and attendance: We anticipated a strong relationship between enrollment in the Bolsa Família program and appointment attendance. However, the data did not support this hypothesis, as attendance rates were similar regardless of grant status.

  • Getting an SMS message: Receiving an SMS reminder was expected to influence attendance positively. Interestingly, our visualizations indicated that patients who did not receive a message had slightly higher attendance rates, though this finding requires further investigation.

  • Degree of disability: The degree of disability appeared to have no effect on attendance, with attendance and absence rates consistent across all levels of disability.

  • Age and chronic diseases: Similarly, no significant relationship was found between the presence of chronic diseases and appointment attendance.

While we did not find definitive relationships between the variables studied and appointment attendance, these findings should be interpreted with caution. It is possible that other unexamined factors or more nuanced interactions between variables could play a role in influencing attendance. Additionally, limitations in the dataset or methodology may have impacted the results.

All things considered, this investigation provides preliminary insights into patient behavior that could inform future research and help improve the delivery of healthcare services in Brazil. Further studies with more comprehensive data and refined analytical approaches are needed to draw more conclusive findings.
